<font color="#FF0000">SEMINAR: 3RD EVENING SPEAKERS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 31 14:53:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The third evening of our seminar was spent in discussions with veterans and civilians with direct involvement in the reality and aftermath of combat.<br><br>
We first heard from a veteran of three wars. Our speaker served in the U.S. Merchant Marine and in the United States Navy during World War II, served as a USN Seabee during the Korean War, and served as a USN Seabee in Vietnam in 1969. Throughout the United States today, three-war veterans are very few in number so our guest provided a unique perspective on similarities-differences between World War II and the Vietnam War. <br><br>
Our next speaker served in the United States Marine in Vietnam as part of an aviation unit. He spoke of the variable life veterans experienced while one base, and the difficulties and realities of coming under enemy rocket and mortar attack -- when things got wild very quickly. <br><br>
The third speaker was a member of Company B, 1st Btalion, 506th Infantry, 101st Airborn Division in Viet Nam.  His major combat campaigns in Viet Nam included, Apache Snow, in the A Shau Valley. His unit was among those that engaged the enemy at Hamburger Hill.His was a very telling experience, given the initial design of the A Shau Valley campaign, and the subsequent withdrawal of troops that had taken the hill.... at such a terrble price.... Our speaker was extremely eloquent and effective, and it was the first time that he had told his story in public. All attending felt the passion and emotion... the joy of shared bonds among veterans, the losses that are difficult to measure even with the passage of more than 20 years. <br><br>
Our next speaker was born and raised in Viet Nam. During the Tet Offensive of 1968, he and his family lived in the city of Hué, where he survived the Communist attack, as well as the South Vietnamese-American counter-attack. He spoke eloquently about the terror at Hue, of the loss of family members and close friends, and of the difficulty of surviving under intense, heavy bombardment. He challenged the students to think and ask: what was the result, not only of the Tet Offensive, but of the Vietnam War in general? Were the people -- the rural people -- any better off under the South or under the North? His was a view of sadness.... of the waste caused by war. He ended with a poignant, descriptive memory of how on the Vietnamese Day to remember the Dead, family members light candles on small paper boats and set them adrift down the river at Hue.... and how many thousands and thousands and thousands of lights flickered in the evening.... commemorating the souls lost....<br><br>
Our final speaker was the State of California and Hawaii Coordinator of the National League of Families of American Prisoners and Missing in Southeast Asia. Her husband was killed in 1968 during combat during the Tet Offensive at the Battle of Hüe. She presented the views of the National League, and urged the government of Vietnam to be more forthcoming in releasing information about MIAs and remains of American veterans. <br><br>
After the presentations, each speaker met with the student teams and exchanged views on the student sub-topics.<br><br>
We will be interviewing veterans and Vietnamese-Americans at the TET festival, held at the Florin Mall, in south Sacramento, this Saturday and Sunday.
